  "body": "<!-- Have you done the following? -->\n<!--   * read the Code of Conduct? By filing an Issue, you are expected to -->  \n<!--     comply with it, including treating everyone with respect: -->\n<!--     https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/main/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md -->\n<!--   * Reproduced the issue in the latest version of the software -->\n<!--   * Read the debugging docs: https://besu.hyperledger.org/en/stable/HowTo/Monitor/Logging/ -->\n<!--   * Duplicate Issue check:  https://github.com/search?q=+is%3Aissue+repo%3Ahyperledger/Besu -->\n<!-- Note:  Not all sections will apply to all issue types. -->\n\n### Description\nCurrently besu leverages the typical basic forward sync strategies for the merge.  Meaning we use full-sync, fast-sync and snap-sync and will sync up to the latest head block from our peers.  However post-merge, when besu syncs a new instance it should stop at the terminal-total-difficulty block and await direction from a consensus client regarding what target to forward-sync to.\n\nHanding the concurrent sync of execution and consensus clients is still an evolving topic, but to mitigate attacks and zombie mining that might happen post-merge, we can and should implement a different post-TTD sync strategy.  \n\nImplementing this strategy has an added benefit of making bonsai tries more viable for the merge, as we will not have to do an expensive rewind operation to get back to TTD once we start processing forkchoiceUpdated calls from the consensus client.  \n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n\n* incorporatea configured terminal block number and block hash as an initial sync target,\n** in the absence of TTD block number/hash, continue to use heaviest chain criteria for which chain to sync\n* stop initial sync at terminal difficulty, and mark the chain as sync'd until otherwise directed by consensus client\n* taking direction from consensus engine via forkchoiceUpdated for the chain and head to forward sync up to\n\n",
